The main step in calculating the ROC, is picking the "n" value. Short-term traders may choose a small n value, such as nine. Longer-term investors may choose a value such as 200. The n value is how many periods ago the current price is being compared to. Smaller values will see the ROC react more quickly to price changes, but that can also mean more <a data-component="link" data-ordinal="1" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" href="https://www.investopedia.com/terms/f/fakeout.asp">false signals</a>. A larger value means the ROC will react slower, but the signals could be more meaningful when they occur.

The Price Rate of Change (ROC) is classed as a <a data-component="link" data-ordinal="1" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" href="https://www.investopedia.com/terms/m/momentum.asp">momentum</a> or velocity indicator because it measures the strength of price momentum by the rate of change. For example, if a stock's price at the close of trading today is $10, and the closing price five trading days prior was $7, then the five-day ROC is 42.85, calculated as

<span data-value="\\begin{aligned} &amp;( ( 10 - 7 ) \\div 7 ) \\times 100 = 42.85 \\\\ \\end{aligned}">﻿<span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">
